# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diffusion-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, **diffusion models**, also known as **diffusion-based generative models** or **score-based generative models**, are a class of latent variable generative models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A diffusion model consists of two major components: the forward diffusion process, and the reverse sampling process.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The goal of diffusion models is to learn a diffusion process for a given dataset, such that the process can generate new elements that are distributed similarly as the original dataset.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A diffusion model models data as generated by a diffusion process, whereby a new datum performs a random walk with drift through the space of all possible data.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A trained diffusion model can be sampled in many ways, with different efficiency and quality.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] There are various equivalent formalisms, including Markov chains, denoising diffusion probabilistic models, noise conditioned score networks, and stochastic differential equations.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] They are typically trained using variational inference.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The model responsible for denoising is typically called its "backbone".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The backbone may be of any kind, but they are typically U-nets or transformers.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] As of 2024, diffusion models are mainly used for computer vision tasks, including image denoising, inpainting, super-resolution, image generation, and video generation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] These typically involve training a neural network to sequentially denoise images blurred with Gaussian noise.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The model is trained to reverse the process of adding noise to an image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] After training to convergence, it can be used for image generation by starting with an image composed of random noise, and applying the network iteratively to denoise the image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Diffusion-based image generators have seen widespread commercial interest, such as Stable Diffusion and DALL-E.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] These models typically combine diffusion models with other models, such as text-encoders and cross-attention modules to allow text-conditioned generation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Other than computer vision, diffusion models have also found applications in natural language processing such as text generation and summarization, sound generation, and reinforcement learning.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Diffusion models were introduced in 2015 as a method to train a model that can sample from a highly complex probability distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] They used techniques from non-equilibrium thermodynamics, especially diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Consider, for example, how one might model the distribution of all naturally occurring photos.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A model that can approximately undo the diffusion can then be used to sample from the original distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This is studied in "non-equilibrium" thermodynamics, as the starting distribution is not in equilibrium, unlike the final distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This is just the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution of particles in a potential well $V(x)={\frac {1}{2}}\|x\|^{2}$ at temperature 1.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The initial distribution, being very much out of equilibrium, would diffuse towards the equilibrium distribution, making biased random steps that are a sum of pure randomness (like a Brownian walker) and gradient descent down the potential well.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The randomness is necessary: if the particles were to undergo only gradient descent, then they will all fall to the origin, collapsing the distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The 2020 paper proposed the Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM), which improves upon the previous method by variational inference.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] To present the model, some notation is required.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The values of $\beta _{t}$ are chosen such that for any starting distribution of $x_{0}$ , if it has finite second moment, then $\lim _{t\to \infty }x_{t}|x_{0}$ converges to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In particular, we note that $x_{1:T}|x_{0}$ is a Gaussian process, which affords us considerable freedom in reparameterization.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] That is, after a long enough diffusion process, we end up with some $x_{T}$ that is very close to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , with all traces of the original $x_{0}\sim q$ gone.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] We also know that these are independent.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] There are 5 variables ${\textstyle x_{0},x_{t-1},x_{t},z,z'}$ and two linear equations.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The two sources of randomness are ${\textstyle z,z'}$ , which can be reparameterized by rotation, since the IID Gaussian distribution is rotationally symmetric.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] By plugging in the equations, we can solve for the first reparameterization: $x_{t}={\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}x_{0}+\underbrace {{\sqrt {\alpha _{t}-{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}z+{\sqrt {1-\alpha _{t}}}z'} _{=\sigma _{t}z''}$ where ${\textstyle z''}$ is a Gaussian with mean zero and variance one.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The key idea of DDPM is to use a neural network parametrized by $\theta$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] To do that, we use maximum likelihood estimation with variational inference.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This allows us to perform variational inference.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Define the loss function $L(\theta ):=-E_{x_{0:T}\sim q}[\ln p_{\theta }(x_{0:T})-\ln q(x_{1:T}|x_{0})]$ and now the goal is to minimize the loss by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Now we see that estimating $x_{0}$ is equivalent to estimating z .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The DDPM paper suggested not learning it (since it resulted in "unstable training and poorer sample quality"), but fixing it at some value $\Sigma _{\theta }(x_{t},t)=\zeta _{t}^{2}I$ , where either $\zeta _{t}^{2}=\beta _{t}{\text{ or }}{\tilde {\sigma }}_{t}^{2}$ yielded similar performance.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The paper noted empirically that an even simpler loss function $L_{simple,t}=E_{x_{0}\sim q;z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)}\left[\left\|\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)-z\right\|^{2}\right]$ resulted in better models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Score-based generative model is another formulation of diffusion modelling.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] They are also called noise conditional score network (NCSN) or score-matching with Langevin dynamics (SMLD).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Consider the problem of image generation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Let x represent an image, and let $q(x)$ be the probability distribution over all possible images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If we have $q(x)$ itself, then we can say for certain how likely a certain image is.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] However, this is intractable in general.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Most often, we are uninterested in knowing the absolute probability of a certain image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Instead, we are usually only interested in knowing how likely a certain image is compared to its immediate neighbors — e.g. how much more likely is an image of cat compared to some small variants of it?
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Is it more likely if the image contains two whiskers, or three, or with some Gaussian noise added?
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Consequently, we are actually quite uninterested in $q(x)$ itself, but rather, $\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Let the score function be $s(x):=\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ ; then consider what we can do with $s(x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] As it turns out, $s(x)$ allows us to sample from $q(x)$ using thermodynamics.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Specifically, if we have a potential energy function $U(x)=-\ln q(x)$ , and a lot of particles in the potential well, then the distribution at thermodynamic equilibrium is the Boltzmann distribution $q_{U}(x)\propto e^{-U(x)/k_{B}T}=q(x)^{1/k_{B}T}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] At temperature $k_{B}T=1$ , the Boltzmann distribution is exactly $q(x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] So no matter what distribution $x_{0}$ has, the distribution of $x_{t}$ converges in distribution to q as $t\to \infty$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Given a density q , we wish to learn a score function approximation $f_{\theta }\approx \nabla \ln q$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This is **score matching***.* Typically, score matching is formalized as minimizing **Fisher divergence** function $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] By expanding the integral, and performing an integration by parts, $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]=E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }\|^{2}+2\nabla \cdot f_{\theta }]+C$ giving us a loss function, also known as the Hyvärinen scoring rule, that can be minimized by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Suppose we need to model the distribution of images, and we want $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , a white-noise image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Now, most white-noise images do not look like real images, so $q(x_{0})\approx 0$ for large swaths of $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This presents a problem for learning the score function, because if there are no samples around a certain point, then we can't learn the score function at that point.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If we do not know the score function $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})$ at that point, then we cannot impose the time-evolution equation on a particle: $dx_{t}=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})dt+dW_{t}$ To deal with this problem, we perform annealing.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If q is too different from a white-noise distribution, then progressively add noise until it is indistinguishable from one.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] That is, we perform a forward diffusion, then learn the score function, then use the score function to perform a backward diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Now, the equation is exactly a special case of the overdamped Langevin equation $dx_{t}=-{\frac {D}{k_{B}T}}(\nabla _{x}U)dt+{\sqrt {2D}}dW_{t}$ where D is diffusion tensor, T is temperature, and U is potential energy field.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This explains why the phrase "Langevin dynamics" is sometimes used in diffusion models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Now the above equation is for the stochastic motion of a single particle.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Suppose we have a cloud of particles distributed according to q at time $t=0$ , then after a long time, the cloud of particles would settle into the stable distribution of ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Let $\rho _{t}$ be the density of the cloud of particles at time t , then we have $\rho _{0}=q;\quad \rho _{T}\approx {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ and the goal is to somehow reverse the process, so that we can start at the end and diffuse back to the beginning.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] By Fokker-Planck equation, the density of the cloud evolves according to $\partial _{t}\ln \rho _{t}={\frac {1}{2}}\beta (t)\left(n+(x+\nabla \ln \rho _{t})\cdot \nabla \ln \rho _{t}+\Delta \ln \rho _{t}\right)$ where n is the dimension of space, and $\Delta$ is the Laplace operator.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If we have solved $\rho _{t}$ for time $t\in [0,T]$ , then we can exactly reverse the evolution of the cloud.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] then by plugging into the Fokker-Planck equation, we find that $\partial _{t}\rho _{T-t}=\partial _{t}\nu _{t}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Thus this cloud of points is the original cloud, evolving backwards.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] That is, we can quickly sample $x_{t}\sim \rho _{t}$ for any $t\geq 0$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] DDPM and score-based generative models are equivalent.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This means that a network trained using DDPM can be used as a NCSN, and vice versa.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Thus, given a good score-based network, its predicted score is a good prediction of the noise (after scaling by $\sigma _{t}$ ), and thus can be used for denoising.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In DDPM, the sequence of numbers $0=\sigma _{0}<\sigma _{1}<\cdots <\sigma _{T}<1$ is called a (discrete time) **noise schedule**.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In general, consider a strictly increasing monotonic function $\sigma$ of type $\mathbb {R} \to (0,1)$ , such as the sigmoid function.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In that case, a noise schedule is a sequence of real numbers $\lambda _{1}<\lambda _{2}<\cdots <\lambda _{T}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In order to use arbitrary noise schedules, instead of training a noise prediction model $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Similarly, for the noise conditional score network, instead of training $f_{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $f_{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The original DDPM method for generating images is slow, since the forward diffusion process usually takes $T\sim 1000$ to make the distribution of $x_{T}$ to appear close to Gaussian.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] However this means the backward diffusion process also take 1000 steps.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Unlike the forward diffusion process, which can skip steps as $x_{t}|x_{0}$ is Gaussian for all $t\geq 1$ , the backward diffusion process does not allow skipping steps.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Attempting to directly sample $x_{t-2}|x_{t}$ would require us to marginalize out $x_{t-1}$ , which is generally intractable.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] DDIM is a method to take any model trained on DDPM loss, and use it to sample with some steps skipped, sacrificing an adjustable amount of quality.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If we generate the Markovian chain case in DDPM to non-Markovian case, DDIM corresponds to the case that the reverse process has variance equals to 0.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In other words, the reverse process (and also the forward process) is deterministic.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] When using fewer sampling steps, DDIM outperforms DDPM.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In detail, the DDIM sampling method is as follows.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If all $\sigma _{s}'=0$ , then the backward process becomes deterministic, and this special case of DDIM is also called "DDIM".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The original paper noted that when the process is deterministic, samples generated with only 20 steps are already very similar to ones generated with 1000 steps on the high-level.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The original paper recommended defining a single "eta value" $\eta \in [0,1]$ , such that $\sigma _{s}'=\eta {\tilde {\sigma }}_{s}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] When $\eta =1$ , this is the original DDPM.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] When $\eta =0$ , this is the fully deterministic DDIM.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] For intermediate values, the process interpolates between them.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] By the equivalence, the DDIM algorithm also applies for score-based diffusion models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Since the diffusion model is a general method for modelling probability distributions, if one wants to model a distribution over images, one can first encode the images into a lower-dimensional space by an encoder, then use a diffusion model to model the distribution over encoded images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Then to generate an image, one can sample from the diffusion model, then use a decoder to decode it into an image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The encoder-decoder pair is most often a variational autoencoder (VAE).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] proposed various architectural improvements.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] For example, they proposed log-space interpolation during backward sampling.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This parameterization was found to improve performance, as the model can be trained to reach total noise (i.e. $\phi _{t}=90^{\circ }$ ) and then reverse it, whereas the standard parameterization never reaches total noise since ${\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}>0$ is always true.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Classifier guidance was proposed in 2021 to improve class-conditional generation by using a classifier.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The original publication used CLIP text encoders to improve text-conditional image generation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Suppose we wish to sample not from the entire distribution of images, but conditional on the image description.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] We don't want to sample a generic image, but an image that fits the description "black cat with red eyes".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Generally, we want to sample from the distribution $p(x|y)$ , where x ranges over images, and y ranges over classes of images (a description "black cat with red eyes" is just a very detailed class, and a class "cat" is just a very vague description).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Taking the perspective of the noisy channel model, we can understand the process as follows: To generate an image x conditional on description y , we imagine that the requester really had in mind an image x , but the image is passed through a noisy channel and came out garbled, as y .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Image generation is then nothing but inferring which x the requester had in mind.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In other words, conditional image generation is simply "translating from a textual language into a pictorial language".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Then, as in noisy-channel model, we use Bayes theorem to get $p(x|y)\propto p(y|x)p(x)$ in other words, if we have a good model of the space of all images, and a good image-to-class translator, we get a class-to-image translator "for free".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] During the diffusion process, we need to condition on the time, giving $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|y,t)=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(y|x_{t},t)+\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|t)$ Although, usually the classifier model does not depend on time, in which case $p(y|x_{t},t)=p(y|x_{t})$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The classifier-guided diffusion model samples from $p(x|y)$ , which is concentrated around the maximum a posteriori estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(x|y)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If we want to force the model to move towards the maximum likelihood estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ , we can use $p_{\gamma }(x|y)\propto p(y|x)^{\gamma }p(x)$ where $\gamma >0$ is interpretable as *inverse temperature*.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In the context of diffusion models, it is usually called the **guidance scale**.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A high $\gamma$ would force the model to sample from a distribution concentrated around $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This sometimes improves quality of generated images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Note that for CFG, the diffusion model cannot be merely a generative model of the entire data distribution $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] It must be a conditional generative model $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x|y)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] For example, in stable diffusion, the diffusion backbone takes as input both a noisy model $x_{t}$ , a time t , and a conditioning vector y (such as a vector encoding a text prompt), and produces a noise prediction $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},y,t)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Also, if the unconditional generation $\epsilon _{\text{uncond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ is replaced by $\epsilon _{\text{neg cond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t,c')$ , then it results in negative prompting, which pushes the generation away from $c'$ condition.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Given a diffusion model, one may regard it either as a continuous process, and sample from it by integrating a SDE, or one can regard it as a discrete process, and sample from it by iterating the discrete steps.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The choice of the "**noise schedule**" $\beta _{t}$ can also affect the quality of samples.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A noise schedule is a function that sends a natural number to a noise level: $t\mapsto \beta _{t},\quad t\in \{1,2,\dots \},\beta \in (0,1)$ A noise schedule is more often specified by a map $t\mapsto \sigma _{t}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In the DDPM perspective, one can use the DDPM itself (with noise), or DDIM (with adjustable amount of noise).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The case where one adds noise is sometimes called ancestral sampling.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] One can interpolate between noise and no noise.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The amount of noise is denoted $\eta$ ("eta value") in the DDIM paper, with $\eta =0$ denoting no noise (as in *deterministic* DDIM), and $\eta =1$ denoting full noise (as in DDPM).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In the perspective of SDE, one can use any of the numerical integration methods, such as Euler–Maruyama method, Heun's method, linear multistep methods, etc.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Just as in the discrete case, one can add an adjustable amount of noise during the integration.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A survey and comparison of samplers in the context of image generation is in.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Notable variants include Poisson flow generative model, consistency model, critically damped Langevin diffusion, GenPhys, cold diffusion, etc.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The probability path is in fact defined implicitly by the score function $\nabla \ln p_{t}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In denoising diffusion models, the forward process adds noise, and the backward process removes noise.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Both the forward and backward processes are SDEs, though the forward process is integrable in closed-form, so it can be done at no computational cost.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The backward process is not integrable in closed-form, so it must be integrated step-by-step by standard SDE solvers, which can be very expensive.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The probability path in diffusions model is defined through an Itô process and one can retrieve the deterministic process by using the Probability ODE flow formulation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In flow-based diffusion models, the forward process is a deterministic flow along a time-dependent vector field, and the backward process is also a deterministic flow along the same vector field, but going backwards.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] If the vector field is well-behaved, the ODE will also be well-behaved.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The solution $\phi _{t}$ of the above ODE define a probability path $p_{t}=[\phi _{t}]_{\#}\pi _{0}$ by the pushforward measure operator.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The idea of **optimal transport flow** is to construct a probability path minimizing the Wasserstein metric.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The idea of **rectified flow** is to learn a flow model such that the velocity is nearly constant along each flow path.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This is beneficial, because we can integrate along such a vector field with very few steps.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] For example, if an ODE ${\dot {\phi _{t}}}(x)=v_{t}(\phi _{t}(x))$ follows perfectly straight paths, it simplifies to $\phi _{t}(x)=x_{0}+t\cdot v_{0}(x_{0})$ , allowing for exact solutions in one step.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In practice, we cannot reach such perfection, but when the flow field is nearly so, we can take a few large steps instead of many little steps.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] The general idea is to start with two distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ , then construct a flow field $\phi ^{0}=\{\phi _{t}:t\in [0,1]\}$ from it, then repeatedly apply a "reflow" operation to obtain successive flow fields $\phi ^{1},\phi ^{2},\dots$ , each straighter than the previous one.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] When the flow field is straight enough for the application, we stop.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] In rectified flow, by injecting strong priors that intermediate trajectories are straight, it can achieve both theoretical relevance for optimal transport and computational efficiency, as ODEs with straight paths can be simulated precisely without time discretization.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Specifically, rectified flow seeks to match an ODE with the marginal distributions of the **linear interpolation** between points from distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This process ensures that the trajectories closely mirror the density map of $x_{t}$ trajectories but *reroute* at intersections to ensure causality.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] A distinctive aspect of rectified flow is its capability for "**reflow**", which straightens the trajectory of ODE paths.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This "reflow" process not only reduces transport costs but also straightens the paths of rectified flows, making $\phi ^{k}$ paths straighter with increasing k .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] Rectified flow includes a nonlinear extension where linear interpolation $x_{t}$ is replaced with any time-differentiable curve that connects $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$ , given by $x_{t}=\alpha _{t}x_{1}+\beta _{t}x_{0}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] This framework encompasses DDIM and probability flow ODEs as special cases, with particular choices of $\alpha _{t}$ and $\beta _{t}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] However, in the case where the path of $x_{t}$ is not straight, the reflow process no longer ensures a reduction in convex transport costs, and also no longer straighten the paths of $\phi _{t}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] These linear flow formulations were independently discovered and adapted from a different perspective for supervised inverse problems.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] For example, Inversion by Direct Iteration (InDI) formulates image restoration by learning a residual flow ODE that iteratively reverses a linear interpolation between a degraded input and a high-quality target to avoid regression-to-the-mean.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p01] InDI is effective for a variety of image restoration tasks.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For generating images by DDPM, we need a neural network that takes a time t and a noisy image $x_{t}$ , and predicts a noise $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ from it.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Since predicting the noise is the same as predicting the denoised image, then subtracting it from $x_{t}$ , denoising architectures tend to work well.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For example, the U-Net, which was found to be good for denoising images, is often used for denoising diffusion models that generate images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For DDPM, the underlying architecture ("backbone") does not have to be a U-Net.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] It just has to predict the noise somehow.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For example, the diffusion transformer (DiT) uses a Transformer to predict the mean and diagonal covariance of the noise, given the textual conditioning and the partially denoised image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] It is the same as standard U-Net-based denoising diffusion model, with a Transformer replacing the U-Net.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Mixture of experts-Transformer can also be applied.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] DDPM can be used to model general data distributions, not just natural-looking images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For example, Human Motion Diffusion models human motion trajectory by DDPM.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Each human motion trajectory is a sequence of poses, represented by either joint rotations or positions.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] It uses a Transformer network to generate a less noisy trajectory out of a noisy one.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The base diffusion model can only generate unconditionally from the whole distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For example, a diffusion model learned on ImageNet would generate images that look like a random image from ImageNet.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] To generate images from just one category, one would need to impose the condition, and then sample from the conditional distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Whatever condition one wants to impose, one needs to first convert the conditioning into a vector of floating point numbers, then feed it into the underlying diffusion model neural network.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] However, one has freedom in choosing how to convert the conditioning into a vector.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Stable Diffusion, for example, imposes conditioning in the form of cross-attention mechanism, where the query is an intermediate representation of the image in the U-Net, and both key and value are the conditioning vectors.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The conditioning can be selectively applied to only parts of an image, and new kinds of conditionings can be finetuned upon the base model, as used in ControlNet.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] As a particularly simple example, consider image inpainting.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The conditions are ${\tilde {x}}$ , the reference image, and m , the inpainting mask.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Another application of cross-attention mechanism is prompt-to-prompt image editing.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Conditioning is not limited to just generating images from a specific category, or according to a specific caption (as in text-to-image).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For example, demonstrated generating human motion, conditioned on an audio clip of human walking (allowing syncing motion to a soundtrack), or video of human running, or a text description of human motion, etc.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] For how conditional diffusion models are mathematically formulated, see a methodological summary in.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] As generating an image takes a long time, one can try to generate a small image by a base diffusion model, then upscale it by other models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Upscaling can be done by GAN, Transformer, or signal processing methods like Lanczos resampling.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Diffusion models themselves can be used to perform upscaling.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Cascading diffusion model stacks multiple diffusion models one after another, in the style of Progressive GAN.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The lowest level is a standard diffusion model that generate 32x32 image, then the image would be upscaled by a diffusion model specifically trained for upscaling, and the process repeats.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] This section collects some notable diffusion models, and briefly describes their architecture.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The DALL-E series by OpenAI are text-conditional diffusion models of images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The first version of DALL-E (2021) is not actually a diffusion model.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Instead, it uses a Transformer architecture that autoregressively generates a sequence of tokens, which is then converted to an image by the decoder of a discrete VAE.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Released with DALL-E was the CLIP classifier, which was used by DALL-E to rank generated images according to how close the image fits the text.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] GLIDE (2022–03) is a 3.5-billion diffusion model, and a small version was released publicly.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] DALL-E 2 is a 3.5-billion cascaded diffusion model that generates images from text by "inverting the CLIP image encoder", the technique which they termed "unCLIP".
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The unCLIP method contains 4 models: a CLIP image encoder, a CLIP text encoder, an image decoder, and a "prior" model (which can be a diffusion model, or an autoregressive model).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] During training, the prior model is trained to convert CLIP image encodings to CLIP text encodings.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The image decoder is trained to convert CLIP image encodings back to images.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] During inference, a text is converted by the CLIP text encoder to a vector, then it is converted by the prior model to an image encoding, then it is converted by the image decoder to an image.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Sora (2024–02) is a diffusion Transformer model (DiT).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] LTX is a family of open source artificial intelligence video foundation models developed by Lightricks, first released in November 2024.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The latest models, LTX-2, create videos based on user prompts, conditioned on text, images, video or audio - and capable of generating audio and visual in a unified way.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] They were preceded by LTX Video, which was released in 2024 as the company's first text-to-video model.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Stable Diffusion (2022–08), released by Stability AI, consists of a denoising latent diffusion model (860 million parameters), a VAE, and a text encoder.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The denoising network is a U-Net, with cross-attention blocks to allow for conditional image generation.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Stable Diffusion 3 (2024–03) changed the latent diffusion model from the UNet to a Transformer model, and so it is a DiT.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Stable Video 4D (2024–07) is a latent diffusion model for videos of 3D objects.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Imagen (2022) uses a T5-XXL language model to encode the input text into an embedding vector.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] It is a cascaded diffusion model with three sub-models.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The first step denoises a white noise to a 64×64 image, conditional on the embedding vector of the text.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The second step upscales the image by 64×64→256×256, conditional on embedding.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The three denoising networks are all U-Nets.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Muse (2023–01) is not a diffusion model, but an encoder-only Transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Imagen 2 (2023–12) is also diffusion-based.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] It can generate images based on a prompt that mixes images and text.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Veo (2024) generates videos by latent diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] The diffusion is conditioned on a vector that encodes both a text prompt and an image prompt.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Make-A-Video (2022) is a text-to-video diffusion model.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] CM3leon (2023) is not a diffusion model, but an autoregressive causally masked Transformer, with mostly the same architecture as LLaMa-2.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Transfusion (2024) is a Transformer that combines autoregressive text generation and denoising diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Specifically, it generates text autoregressively (with causal masking), and generates images by denoising multiple times over image tokens (with all-to-all attention).
[src:diffusion-models/diffusion-model-machine-learning-p02] Movie Gen (2024) is a series of Diffusion Transformers operating on latent space and by flow matching.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been used for cybercrime, and to deceive and manipulate people through fake news and deepfakes.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models have been trained on copyrighted works without the rightholders' permission.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI systems use large-scale data centers, whose environmental impacts include electronic waste, consumption of fresh water for cooling, and high energy consumption that is estimated to be growing steadily.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The origins of algorithmically generated media can be traced to the development of the Markov chain, which has been used to model natural language since the early 20th century.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Russian mathematician Andrey Markov introduced the concept in 1906, including an analysis of vowel and consonant patterns in *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Once trained on a text corpus, a Markov chain can generate probabilistic text.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] By the early 1970s, artists began using computers to extend generative techniques beyond Markov models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Harold Cohen developed and exhibited works produced by AARON, a pioneering computer program designed to autonomously create paintings.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The terms generative AI planning or generative planning were used in the 1980s and 1990s to refer to AI planning systems, especially computer-aided process planning, used to generate sequences of actions to reach a specified goal.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI planning systems used symbolic AI methods such as state space search and constraint satisfaction and were a "relatively mature" technology by the early 1990s.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] They were used to generate crisis action plans for military use, process plans for manufacturing and decision plans such as in prototype autonomous spacecraft.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Machine learning uses both discriminative models and generative models to predict or generate data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Beginning in the late 2000s and early 2010s, advances in deep learning led to major improvements in image classification, speech recognition, and natural language processing.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Neural networks in this period were typically trained as discriminative models due to the relative difficulty of training generative models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2014, the introduction of models such as the variational autoencoder (VAE) and generative adversarial network (GAN) enabled effective deep generative modeling of complex data such as images.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2017, the Transformer architecture enabled further advances in generative modeling compared to earlier long short-term memory (LSTM) networks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This led to the development of generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) models, beginning with GPT-1 in 2018.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2020, the release of 15.ai, a free web application created by an anonymous MIT researcher that could generate convincing character voices using minimal training data, was one of the earliest publicly available uses for generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The platform is credited as the first mainstream service for audio deepfakes.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2021, DALL-E, a closed-source transformer-based generative model developed by OpenAI, drew widespread attention to text-to-image generation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other projects, including open-source approaches such as VQGAN+CLIP and DALL·E Mini (later renamed Craiyon), made similar systems more accessible to the public.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Dream by Wombo was released at the end of 2021, followed by the releases of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion in 2022.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In November 2022, ChatGPT was released to the public.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, it popularized generative AI for general-purpose text-based tasks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a 2024 survey by marketing research firm Ipsos, Asia–Pacific countries were significantly more optimistic than Western societies about generative AI and show higher adoption rates.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite expressing concerns about privacy and the pace of change, 68% of Asia-Pacific respondents believed that AI was having a positive impact on the world, compared to 57% globally.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a survey by SAS and Coleman Parkes Research, as of 2023, 83% of Chinese respondents were using the technology, exceeding both the global average of 54% and the U.S. rate of 65%.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A UN report indicated that Chinese entities filed over 38,000 generative AI patents from 2014 to 2023, more than any other country.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 survey by the Just So Soul social media app reported that 18% of respondents born after 2000 used generative AI "almost every day", and that over 60% of respondents like or love AI-generated content (AIGC), while less than 3% dislike or hate it.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative artificial intelligence has been applied across multiple industries for content creation and automation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In healthcare, generative models are used for drug discovery and the generation of synthetic medical data to train diagnostic systems.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In finance, they are used for report drafting, data generation, and customer service automation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Media and entertainment industries use generative systems for tasks such as music composition, script development, and image or video generation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Researchers and policymakers have raised concerns regarding accuracy, misuse, and impacts on academic and professional work.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Large language models (LLMs) are trained on tokenized text from large corpora and are capable of natural language processing, machine translation, and natural language generation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] LLMs can be used as foundation models for a variety of downstream tasks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] They can also be trained on source code to generate programs from prompts.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2016, DeepMind's WaveNet demonstrated that deep neural networks can generate raw audio waveforms.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This enabled more realistic speech synthesis compared to earlier approaches.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Subsequent systems such as Tacotron 2 demonstrated end-to-end neural text-to-speech generation.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to create visual art.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Such systems are trained on image–text pairs.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Examples include Stable Diffusion, DALL-E, and Midjourney.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to produce photorealistic videos.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Systems such as Runway have demonstrated text-to-video generation capabilities.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can be used for motion planning and robot control by learning from prior data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can assist in automating 3D modeling tasks, including generating 3D assets from text or images.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] World models are neural networks designed to learn representations of physical environments, including spatial and dynamic properties.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Recent multimodal systems have expanded these capabilities by integrating vision, language, and action into unified models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems have been used in mathematics and computer science to generate candidate computer programs, proofs, constructions, or algorithms.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced FunSearch, a method for creating computer programs that solve mathematical and algorithmic problems.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] FunSearch was used to discover new mathematical constructions in the cap set problem and the bin packing problem.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, which was used to discover small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and have been integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an AI system for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] AlphaEvolve uses LLMs to propose code changes, automated evaluators to assess each candidate, and an evolutionary process to iteratively improve algorithms.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced GNoME, a method to propose candidate inorganic crystal structures for computational screening and experimental synthesis in material science.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other material science methods include MatterGen, CDVAE, and CrystalFlow.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative engine optimization (GEO) is the practice of structuring digital content and managing online presence to improve visibility in responses generated by generative AI systems.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The practice influences the way large language models (LLMs) retrieve, summarize, and present information in response to user queries.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Related terms include answer engine optimization (AEO) and artificial intelligence optimization (AIO).
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models are used to power chatbot products such as ChatGPT, programming tools such as GitHub Copilot, text-to-image products such as Midjourney, and text-to-video products such as Runway Gen-2.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI features have been integrated into a variety of existing commercially available products such as Microsoft Office (Microsoft Copilot), Google Photos, and the Adobe Suite (Adobe Firefly).
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI models are also available as open-source software, including Stable Diffusion and the LLaMA language model.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller generative AI models with up to a few billion parameters can run on smartphones, embedded devices, and personal computers.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, LLaMA-7B (a version with 7 billion parameters) can run on a Raspberry Pi 4 and one version of Stable Diffusion can run on an iPhone 11.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Larger models with tens of billions of parameters can run on laptop or desktop computers.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] To achieve an acceptable speed, models of this size may require accelerators such as the GPU chips produced by NVIDIA and AMD or the Neural Engine included in Apple silicon products.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, the 65 billion parameter version of LLaMA can be configured to run on a desktop PC.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The advantages of running generative AI locally include protection of privacy and intellectual property, and avoidance of rate limiting and censorship.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The subreddit r/LocalLLaMA in particular focuses on using consumer-grade gaming graphics cards through such techniques as compression.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Language models with hundreds of billions of parameters, such as GPT-4 or PaLM, typically run on datacenter computers equipped with arrays of GPUs (such as NVIDIA's H100) or AI accelerator chips (such as Google's TPU).
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] These very large models are typically accessed as cloud services over the Internet.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2022, the United States New Export Controls on Advanced Computing and Semiconductors to China imposed restrictions on exports to China of GPU and AI accelerator chips used for generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Chips such as the NVIDIA A800 and the Biren Technology BR104 were developed to meet the requirements of the sanctions.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is free software on the market capable of recognizing text generated by generative artificial intelligence (such as GPTZero), as well as images, audio or video coming from it.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Potential mitigation strategies for detecting generative AI content include digital watermarking, content authentication, information retrieval, and machine learning classifier models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite claims of accuracy, both free and paid AI text detectors have frequently produced false positives, mistakenly accusing students of submitting AI-generated work.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are a generative modeling technique which consist of two neural networks—the generator and the discriminator—trained simultaneously in a competitive setting.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The generator creates synthetic data by transforming random noise into samples that resemble the training dataset.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The discriminator is trained to distinguish the authentic data from synthetic data produced by the generator.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The two models engage in a minimax game: the generator aims to create increasingly realistic data to "fool" the discriminator, while the discriminator improves its ability to distinguish real from fake data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This continuous training setup enables the generator to produce high-quality and realistic outputs.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Variational autoencoders (VAEs) are deep learning models that probabilistically encode data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] They are typically used for tasks such as noise reduction from images, data compression, identifying unusual patterns, and facial recognition.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike standard autoencoders, which compress input data into a fixed latent representation, VAEs model the latent space as a probability distribution, allowing for smooth sampling and interpolation between data points.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The encoder ("recognition model") maps input data to a latent space, producing means and variances that define a probability distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The decoder ("generative model") samples from this latent distribution and attempts to reconstruct the original input.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Transformers became the foundation for the generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) series developed by OpenAI, replacing traditional recurrent and convolutional models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The self-attention mechanism enables the model to determine the relative importance of each token in a sequence when predicting the next token, thereby improving contextual understanding.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike recurrent neural networks, transformers process tokens in parallel, which improves training efficiency and scalability.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, a group of companies including OpenAI, Alphabet, and Meta signed a voluntary agreement with the Biden administration in July 2023 to watermark AI-generated content.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In October 2023, Executive Order 14110 applied the Defense Production Act to require all US companies to report information to the federal government when training certain high-impact AI models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the European Union (EU), the Artificial Intelligence Act includes requirements to disclose copyrighted material used to train generative AI systems, and to label any AI-generated output as such.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In China, the Interim Measures for the Management of Generative AI Services introduced by the Cyberspace Administration of China regulates any public-facing generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] It includes requirements to watermark generated images or videos, regulations on training data and label quality, restrictions on personal data collection, and a guideline that generative AI services must "adhere to socialist core values".
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems such as ChatGPT and Midjourney are trained on large, publicly available datasets that include copyrighted works.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI developers have argued that such training is protected under fair use, while copyright holders have argued that it infringes their rights.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Proponents of fair use training have argued that it is a transformative use and does not involve making copies of copyrighted works available to the public.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Critics have argued that image generators such as Midjourney can create nearly-identical copies of some copyrighted images, and that generative AI programs compete with the content they are trained on.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] As of 2024, several lawsuits related to the use of copyrighted material in training are ongoing.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Getty Images has sued Stability AI over the use of its images to train Stable Diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Both the Authors Guild and The New York Times have sued Microsoft and OpenAI over the use of their works to train ChatGPT.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A separate question is whether AI-generated works can qualify for copyright protection.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The United States Copyright Office has ruled that works created by artificial intelligence without any human input cannot be copyrighted, because they lack human authorship.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Some legal professionals have suggested that *Naruto v.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals held that non-humans cannot be copyright holders of artistic works, could be a potential precedent in copyright litigation over works created by generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the office has also begun taking public input to determine if these rules need to be refined for generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Whether such modifications rise to the minimum standard of originality required under Feist will depend on a case-by-case determination.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In those cases where they do, the output should be copyrightable" Subsequently, the USCO registered the first visual artwork to be composed of entirely AI-generated materials, titled "A Single Piece of American Cheese".
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The development of generative AI has raised concerns from governments, businesses, and individuals, resulting in protests, legal actions, calls to pause AI experiments, and actions by multiple governments.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In addition, generative AI has a significant carbon footprint.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study presented in the 2026 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems found that overreliance on generative AI can decrease one's ability to discern misinformation, the study tracked participants, mostly from the UK and US, for a period of 4 weeks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to generate and modify academic prose, paraphrase sources, and translate languages.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The use of generative AI in a classroom setting has challenged traditional definitions of academic plagiarism, leading to a "cat-and-mouse" dynamic between students using AI and institutions attempting to detect it.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the immediate wake of ChatGPT's release, many school districts and universities issued temporary bans on the technology, though many institutions have since moved toward policies of managed integration.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the implementation of these policies often lacks clarity.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Research suggests that the burden of interpreting "acceptable use" frequently falls on individual students and teachers, creating an environment where academic honesty becomes difficult to define and enforce.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A commonly proposed use for teachers is grading and giving feedback.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies like Pearson and ETS use AI to score grammar, mechanics, usage, and style, but not for main ideas or overall structure.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The National Council of Teachers of English stated that machine scoring makes students feel their writing is not worth reading.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI scoring has also given unfair results for students from different ethnic backgrounds.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, it was reported that image generation AI has resulted in 70% of the jobs for video game illustrators in China being lost.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In July 2023, developments in generative AI contributed to the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Fran Drescher, president of the Screen Actors Guild, declared that "artificial intelligence poses an existential threat to creative professions" during the 2023 SAG-AFTRA strike.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Voice generation AI has been seen as a potential challenge to the voice acting sector.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, a 2025 study concluded that the US labor market had so far not experienced a discernible disruption from generative AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Another study reported that Danish workers who used chatbots saved 2.8% of their time on average, and found no significant change in earnings or hours worked.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, *Futurism* broke the story that CNET had been using an undisclosed internal AI tool to write at least 77 of its stories; after the news broke, CNET posted corrections to 41 of the stories.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, *Die Aktuelle* published an AI-generated fake interview of Michael Schumacher.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2024, *Futurism* noted that a content management system video by AdVon Commerce, which had used generative AI to produce articles for many of the aforementioned outlets, appeared to show that they "had produced tens of thousands of articles for more than 150 publishers".
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, a report from the American Sunlight Project stated that Pravda network was publishing as many as 10,000 articles a day, and concluded that much of this content aimed to push Russian narratives into large language models through their training data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2024, Reuters Institute published its *Digital News Report for 2024*.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a survey of people in America and Europe, Reuters Institute reports that 52% and 47% respectively are uncomfortable with news produced by "mostly AI with some human oversight", and 23% and 15% respectively report being comfortable.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] 42% of Americans and 33% of Europeans reported that they were comfortable with news produced by "mainly human with some help from AI".
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The results of global surveys reported that people were more uncomfortable with news topics including politics (46%), crime (43%), and local news (37%) produced by AI than other news topics.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2025 Pew Research Survey found roughly half of all U.S. adults say that AI will have a very (24%) or somewhat (26%) negative impact on the news people get in the U.S. over the next 20 years.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A language model may associate certain professions with specific genders if such patterns are prevalent in the data.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similarly, image generation systems prompted with terms such as "a photo of a CEO" have been observed to disproportionately generate images of white male individuals when trained on biased datasets.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI software, when using voice recognition software in particular, struggles to recognize and understand speech impediments.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, people with a stutter struggle to activate voice-activated assistants such as Gemini and Siri due to how the software was trained.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies that use AI systems to hire for new positions also filter out people with accents and speech due to voice recognition software incorrectly transcribing how candidates speak during the interview process.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Because of this, people with disabilities and uncommon accents don't often make it to a human interviewer when these generative AI systems are used.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This is due to many AI models being trained and produced in the United States, and therefore, off of American accents.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes (a portmanteau of "deep learning" and "fake") are AI-generated media that take a person in an existing image or video and replace them with someone else's likeness using artificial neural networks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes have garnered widespread attention and concerns for their uses in deepfake celebrity pornographic videos, revenge porn, fake news, hoaxes, health disinformation, financial fraud, and covert foreign election interference.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Instances of users abusing software to generate controversial statements in the vocal style of celebrities, public officials, and other famous individuals have raised ethical concerns over voice generation AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In response, companies such as ElevenLabs have stated that they would work on mitigating potential abuse through safeguards and identity verification.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Concerns and fandoms have spawned from AI-generated music.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The same software used to clone voices has been used on famous musicians' voices to create songs that mimic their voices, gaining both tremendous popularity and criticism.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similar techniques have also been used to create improved quality or full-length versions of songs that have been leaked or have yet to be released.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been noted for its use by state-sponsored propaganda campaigns in information laundering.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a 2025 report by Graphika, generative AI is used to launder articles from Chinese state media such as China Global Television Network through various social media sites in an attempt to disguise the articles' origin.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A paper published by researchers at Amazon Web Services AI Labs found that over 57% of sentences from a sample of over 6 billion sentences from Common Crawl, a snapshot of web pages, were machine translated.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many of these automated translations were seen as lower quality, especially for sentences that were translated into at least three languages.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Wolof, Xhosa) were translated across more languages than higher-resource languages (ex.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI tools led to an explosion of AI-generated content across multiple domains.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study from University College London estimated that in 2023, more than 60,000 scholarly articles—over 1% of all publications—were likely written with LLM assistance.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to Stanford University's Institute for Human-Centered AI, approximately 17.5% of newly published computer science papers and 16.9% of peer review text now incorporate content generated by LLMs.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] If AI-generated content is included in new data crawls from the Internet for additional training of AI models, defects in the resulting models may occur.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training an AI model exclusively on the output of another AI model produces a lower-quality model.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Repeating this process, where each new model is trained on the previous model's output, leads to progressive degradation and eventually results in a "model collapse" after multiple iterations.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] On the other side, synthetic data can be deployed to train machine learning models while preserving user privacy.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The approach is not limited to text generation; image generation has been employed to train computer vision models.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many websites that allow explicit AI generated images or videos have been created, and this has been used to create illegal content, such as rape, child sexual abuse material, necrophilia, and zoophilia.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI's ability to create realistic fake content has been exploited in numerous types of cybercrime, including phishing scams.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfake video and audio have been used to create disinformation and fraud.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2020, former Google click fraud czar Shuman Ghosemajumder argued that once deepfake videos become perfectly realistic, they would stop appearing remarkable to viewers, potentially leading to uncritical acceptance of false information.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, large language models and other forms of text-generation AI have been used to create fake reviews of e-commerce websites to boost ratings.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Cybercriminals have created large language models focused on fraud, including WormGPT and FraudGPT.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study showed that generative AI can be vulnerable to jailbreaks, reverse psychology and prompt injection attacks, enabling attackers to obtain help with harmful requests, such as for crafting social engineering and phishing attacks.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, other researchers have demonstrated that open-source models can be fine-tuned to remove their safety restrictions at low cost.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Israel signed a $6 million contract with the US-based firm Clock Tower X that aimed to influence ChatGPT, Gemini and Grok by spreading pro-Israel information onto social media and websites.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This was in an attempt to take advantage of the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technique which is used by LLMs to provide more up-to-date information.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from covered service providers, including some AI service providers, regardless of where the data is physically stored.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Courts can require parent companies to provide data held by their subsidiaries, and such orders may be accompanied by nondisclosure requirements preventing the provider from notifying affected users.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] This framework has been described in legal commentary as creating legal tension with Article 48 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] As a result, service providers operating in both jurisdictions may face competing legal obligations under U.S. and EU law.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI has a significant carbon footprint due to growing energy consumption from both training and usage.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is also concern that these impacts may increase as these models are incorporated into widely used search engines such as Google Search and Bing, as chatbots and other applications become more popular, and as models need to be retrained.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training frontier AI models requires an enormous amount of computing power.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Usually only Big Tech companies have the financial resources to make such investments.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller start-ups such as Cohere and OpenAI end up buying access to data centers from Google and Microsoft respectively.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Tools such as GPTZero can detect content generated by AI.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, they can also make false accusations (false positives).
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] Digital watermarking is a technique that improves detection accuracy.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] It works by altering the generated content at the source, in subtle ways which can be detected by corresponding software.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, OpenAI developed a watermarking tool for ChatGPT.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] They didn't release it, because they worried that users would switch to competitors.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] They also argued that it would be easy to circumvent, for example by asking another AI to rephrase.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2025, the Cyberspace Administration of China issued rules, requiring online service providers to label AI content.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Google deployed its watermarking tool, SynthID.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] It marks output from Gemini (text), Imagen (images), and Veo (video).
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] To detect output from these products, one uses Google's "SynthID detector" portal.
[src:diffusion-models/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2025, users mistakenly accused gaming companies of using generative AI for the video games *Little Droid* and *Catly*.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The **Latent Diffusion Model** (**LDM**) is a diffusion model architecture developed by the CompVis (Computer Vision & Learning) group at LMU Munich.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Introduced in 2015, diffusion models (DMs) are trained with the objective of removing successive applications of noise (commonly Gaussian) on training images.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The LDM is an improvement on standard DM by performing diffusion modeling in a latent space, and by allowing self-attention and cross-attention conditioning.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] LDMs are widely used in practical diffusion models.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] For instance, Stable Diffusion versions 1.1 to 2.1 were based on the LDM architecture.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Diffusion models were introduced in 2015 as a method to learn a model that can sample from a highly complex probability distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] It was accompanied by a software implementation in Theano.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] A 2019 paper proposed the **noise conditional score network (NCSN)** or score-matching with Langevin dynamics (SMLD).
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The paper was accompanied by a software package written in PyTorch release on GitHub.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] A 2020 paper proposed the **Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM)**, which improves upon the previous method by variational inference.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The paper was accompanied by a software package written in TensorFlow release on GitHub.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] It was reimplemented in PyTorch by lucidrains.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] On December 20, 2021, the LDM paper was published on arXiv, and both **Stable Diffusion** and LDM repositories were published on GitHub.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] However, they remained roughly the same.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Substantial information concerning Stable Diffusion v1 was only added to GitHub on August 10, 2022.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] All of Stable Diffusion (SD) versions 1.1 to XL were particular instantiations of the LDM architecture.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] SD 1.1 to 1.4 were released by CompVis in August 2022.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] SD 1.1 was a LDM trained on the laion2B-en dataset.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] SD 1.1 was finetuned to 1.2 on more aesthetic images.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] SD 1.2 was finetuned to 1.3, 1.4 and 1.5, with 10% of text-conditioning dropped, to improve classifier-free guidance.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] SD 1.5 was released by RunwayML in October 2022.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] While the LDM can work for generating arbitrary data conditional on arbitrary data, for concreteness, we describe its operation in conditional text-to-image generation.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] LDM consists of a variational autoencoder (VAE), a modified U-Net, and a text encoder.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The VAE encoder compresses the image from pixel space to a smaller dimensional latent space, capturing a more fundamental semantic meaning of the image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Gaussian noise is iteratively applied to the compressed latent representation during forward diffusion.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The U-Net block, composed of a ResNet backbone, denoises the output from forward diffusion backwards to obtain a latent representation.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Finally, the VAE decoder generates the final image by converting the representation back into pixel space.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The denoising step can be conditioned on a string of text, an image, or another modality.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The encoded conditioning data is exposed to denoising U-Nets via a cross-attention mechanism.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] For conditioning on text, the fixed, a pretrained CLIP ViT-L/14 text encoder is used to transform text prompts to an embedding space.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] To compress the image data, a variational autoencoder (VAE) is first trained on a dataset of images.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The encoder part of the VAE takes an image as input and outputs a lower-dimensional latent representation of the image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] This latent representation is then used as input to the U-Net.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Once the model is trained, the encoder is used to encode images into latent representations, and the decoder is used to decode latent representations back into images.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Let the encoder and the decoder of the VAE be $E,D$ .
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] To encode an RGB image, its three channels are divided by the maximum value, resulting in a tensor x of shape $(3,512,512)$ with all entries within range $[0,1]$ .
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The encoded vector is $0.18215\times E(2x-1)$ , with shape $(4,64,64)$ , where 0.18215 is a hyperparameter, which the original authors picked to roughly whiten the encoded vector to roughly unit variance.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Conversely, given a latent tensor y , the decoded image is $(D(y/0.18125)+1)/2$ , then clipped to the range $[0,1]$ .
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] In the implemented version, the encoder is a convolutional neural network (CNN) with a single self-attention mechanism near the end.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] It takes a tensor of shape $(3,H,W)$ and outputs a tensor of shape $(8,H/8,W/8)$ , being the concatenation of the predicted mean and variance of the latent vector, each of shape $(4,H/8,W/8)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The variance is used in training, but after training, usually only the mean is taken, with the variance discarded.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The decoder is also a CNN with a single self-attention mechanism near the end.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] It takes a tensor of shape $(4,H/8,W/8)$ and outputs a tensor of shape $(3,H,W)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Each run through the U-Net backbone produces a predicted noise vector.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] This noise vector is scaled down and subtracted away from the latent image array, resulting in a slightly less noisy latent image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The denoising is repeated according to a denoising schedule ("noise schedule"), and the output of the last step is processed by the VAE decoder into a finished image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Similar to the standard U-Net, the U-Net backbone used in the SD 1.5 is essentially composed of down-scaling layers followed by up-scaling layers.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] However, the U-Net backbone has additional modules to allow for it to handle the embedding.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The detailed architecture may be found in.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The LDM is trained by using a Markov chain to gradually add noise to the training images.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The model is then trained to reverse this process, starting with a noisy image and gradually removing the noise until it recovers the original image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The model is trained to minimize the difference between the predicted noise and the actual noise added at each step.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] This is typically done using a mean squared error (MSE) loss function.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] Once the model is trained, it can be used to generate new images by simply running the reverse diffusion process starting from a random noise sample.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] The model gradually removes the noise from the sample, guided by the learned noise distribution, until it generates a final image.
[src:diffusion-models/latent-diffusion-model] See the diffusion model page for details.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In probability theory and statistics, a **Markov chain** or **Markov process** is a stochastic process describing a sequence of possible events in which the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Informally, this may be thought of as, "What happens next depends only on the state of affairs *now*." A countably infinite sequence, in which the chain moves state at discrete time steps, gives a discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time process is called a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes are named in honor of the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov chains have many applications as statistical models of real-world processes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The adjectives *Markovian* and *Markov* are used to describe something that is related to a Markov process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov process is a stochastic process that satisfies the Markov property (sometimes characterized as "memorylessness").
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In simpler terms, it is a process for which predictions can be made regarding future outcomes based solely on its present state and—most importantly—such predictions are just as good as the ones that could be made knowing the process's full history.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, conditional on the present state of the system, its future and past states are independent.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is a type of Markov process that has either a discrete state space or a discrete index set (often representing time), but the precise definition of a Markov chain varies.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The system's state space and time parameter index need to be specified.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Note that there is no definitive agreement in the literature on the use of some of the terms that signify special cases of Markov processes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Usually the term "Markov chain" is reserved for a process with a discrete set of times, that is, a **discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC)**, but a few authors use the term "Markov process" to refer to a **continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC)** without explicit mention.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In addition, there are other extensions of Markov processes that are referred to as such but do not necessarily fall within any of these four categories (see Markov model).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Moreover, the time index need not necessarily be real-valued; like with the state space, there are conceivable processes that move through index sets with other mathematical constructs.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Notice that the general state space continuous-time Markov chain is general to such a degree that it has no designated term.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] While the time parameter is usually discrete, the state space of a Markov chain does not have any generally agreed-on restrictions: the term may refer to a process on an arbitrary state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] However, many applications of Markov chains employ finite or countably infinite state spaces, which have a more straightforward statistical analysis.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Besides time-index and state-space parameters, there are many other variations, extensions and generalizations (see Variations).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] For simplicity, most of this article concentrates on the discrete-time, discrete state-space case, unless mentioned otherwise.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The changes of state of the system are called transitions.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The probabilities associated with various state changes are called transition probabilities.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The process is characterized by a state space, a transition matrix describing the probabilities of particular transitions, and an initial state (or initial distribution) across the state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] By convention, we assume all possible states and transitions have been included in the definition of the process, so there is always a next state, and the process does not terminate.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A discrete-time random process involves a system which is in a certain state at each step, with the state changing randomly between steps.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The steps are often thought of as moments in time, but they can equally well refer to physical distance or any other discrete measurement.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Formally, the steps are the integers or natural numbers, and the random process is a mapping of these to states.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The Markov property states that the conditional probability distribution for the system at the next step (and in fact at all future steps) depends only on the current state of the system, and not additionally on the state of the system at previous steps.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since the system changes randomly, it is generally impossible to predict with certainty the state of a Markov chain at a given point in the future.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] However, the statistical properties of the system's future can be predicted.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In many applications, it is these statistical properties that are important.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Markov studied Markov processes in the early 20th century, publishing his first paper on the topic in 1906.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes in continuous time were discovered long before his work in the early 20th century in the form of the Poisson process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov was interested in studying an extension of independent random sequences, motivated by a disagreement with Pavel Nekrasov who claimed independence was necessary for the weak law of large numbers to hold.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov later used Markov chains to study the distribution of vowels in Eugene Onegin, written by Alexander Pushkin, and proved a central limit theorem for such chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In 1912 Henri Poincaré studied Markov chains on finite groups with an aim to study card shuffling.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Other early uses of Markov chains include a diffusion model, introduced by Paul and Tatyana Ehrenfest in 1907, and a branching process, introduced by Francis Galton and Henry William Watson in 1873, preceding the work of Markov.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] After the work of Galton and Watson, it was later revealed that their branching process had been independently discovered and studied around three decades earlier by Irénée-Jules Bienaymé.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Starting in 1928, Maurice Fréchet became interested in Markov chains, eventually resulting in him publishing in 1938 a detailed study on Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Kolmogorov developed in a 1931 paper a large part of the early theory of continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov was partly inspired by Louis Bachelier's 1900 work on fluctuations in the stock market as well as Norbert Wiener's work on Einstein's model of Brownian movement.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] He introduced and studied a particular set of Markov processes known as diffusion processes, where he derived a set of differential equations describing the processes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Independent of Kolmogorov's work, Sydney Chapman derived in a 1928 paper an equation, now called the Chapman–Kolmogorov equation, in a less mathematically rigorous way than Kolmogorov, while studying Brownian movement.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The differential equations are now called the Kolmogorov equations or the Kolmogorov–Chapman equations.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Other mathematicians who contributed significantly to the foundations of Markov processes include William Feller, starting in 1930s, and then later Eugene Dynkin, starting in the 1950s.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that there is a coin purse containing five coins worth 25¢ (quarters), five coins worth 10¢ (dimes) and five coins worth 5¢ (nickels).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] One by one, coins are randomly drawn from the purse and are set on a table.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If $X_{n}$ represents the total value of the coins set on the table after n draws, with $X_{0}=0$ , then the sequence $\{X_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ is *not* a Markov process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] To see why this is the case, suppose that in the first six draws, all five nickels and a quarter are drawn.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If we know not just $X_{6}$ , but the earlier values as well, then we can determine which coins have been drawn, and we know that the next coin will not be a nickel; so we can determine that $X_{7}\geq \$0.60$ with probability 1.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] But if we do not know the earlier values, then based only on the value $X_{6}$ we might guess that we had drawn four dimes and two nickels, in which case it would certainly be possible to draw another nickel next.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Thus, our guesses about $X_{7}$ are impacted by our knowledge of values prior to $X_{6}$ .
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] However, it is possible to model this scenario as a Markov process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Instead of defining $X_{n}$ to represent the *total value* of the coins on the table, we could define $X_{n}$ to represent the *count* of the various coin types on the table.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] For instance, $X_{6}=1,0,5$ could be defined to represent the state where there is one quarter, zero dimes, and five nickels on the table after 6 one-by-one draws.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This new model could be represented by $6\times 6\times 6=216$ possible states, where each state represents the number of coins of each type (from 0 to 5) that are on the table.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that the first draw results in state $X_{1}=0,1,0$ .
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The probability of achieving $X_{2}$ now depends on $X_{1}$ ; for example, the state $X_{2}=1,0,1$ is not possible.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] After the second draw, the third draw depends on which coins have so far been drawn, but no longer only on the coins that were drawn for the first state (since probabilistically important information has since been added to the scenario).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In this way, the likelihood of the $X_{n}=i,j,k$ state depends exclusively on the outcome of the $X_{n-1}=\ell ,m,p$ state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The possible values of *X**i* form a countable set *S* called the state space of the chain.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since each row of **P** sums to one and all elements are non-negative, **P** is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] is a normalized ( ${\textstyle \sum _{i}\pi _{i}=1}$ ) multiple of a left eigenvector **e** of the transition matrix **P** with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If there is more than one unit eigenvector then a weighted sum of the corresponding stationary states is also a stationary state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] But for a Markov chain one is usually more interested in a stationary state that is the limit of the sequence of distributions for some initial distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The values of a stationary distribution $\textstyle \pi _{i}$ are associated with the state space of **P** and its eigenvectors have their relative proportions preserved.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since the components of π are positive and the constraint that their sum is unity can be rewritten as ${\textstyle \sum _{i}1\cdot \pi _{i}=1}$ we see that the dot product of π with a vector whose components are all 1 is unity and that π lies on a simplex.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is time-homogeneous, then the transition matrix **P** is the same after each step, so the *k*-step transition probability can be computed as the *k*-th power of the transition matrix, **P***k*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is irreducible and aperiodic, then there is a unique stationary distribution π.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] where **1** is the column vector with all entries equal to 1.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This is stated by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If, by whatever means, ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }\mathbf {P} ^{k}}$ is found, then the stationary distribution of the Markov chain in question can be easily determined for any starting distribution, as will be explained below.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Because there are a number of different special cases to consider, the process of finding this limit if it exists can be a lengthy task.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] However, there are many techniques that can assist in finding this limit.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size *n*, and **0***n*,*n* is the zero matrix of size *n*×*n*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Multiplying together stochastic matrices always yields another stochastic matrix, so **Q** must be a stochastic matrix (see the definition above).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] It is sometimes sufficient to use the matrix equation above and the fact that **Q** is a stochastic matrix to solve for **Q**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Here is one method for doing so: first, define the function *f*(**A**) to return the matrix **A** with its right-most column replaced with all 1's.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] One thing to notice is that if **P** has an element **P***i*,*i* on its main diagonal that is equal to 1 and the *i*th row or column is otherwise filled with 0's, then that row or column will remain unchanged in all of the subsequent powers **P***k*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Hence, the *i*th row or column of **Q** will have the 1 and the 0's in the same positions as in **P**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] As stated earlier, from the equation ${\boldsymbol {\pi }}={\boldsymbol {\pi }}\mathbf {P} ,$ (if exists) the stationary (or steady state) distribution **π** is a left eigenvector of row stochastic matrix **P**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Then assuming that **P** is diagonalizable or equivalently that **P** has *n* linearly independent eigenvectors, speed of convergence is elaborated as follows.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Let **U** be the matrix of eigenvectors (each normalized to having an L2 norm equal to 1) where each column is a left eigenvector of **P** and let **Σ** be the diagonal matrix of left eigenvalues of **P**, that is, **Σ** = diag(*λ*1,*λ*2,*λ*3,...,*λ**n*).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since **P** is a row stochastic matrix, its largest left eigenvalue is 1.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If there is a unique stationary distribution, then the largest eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector is unique too (because there is no other **π** which solves the stationary distribution equation above).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Let **u***i* be the *i*-th column of **U** matrix, that is, **u***i* is the left eigenvector of **P** corresponding to λ*i*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If we multiply **x** with **P** from right and continue this operation with the results, in the end we get the stationary distribution **π**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since **π** is parallel to **u**1(normalized by L2 norm) and **π**(*k*) is a probability vector, **π**(*k*) approaches to **a**1 **u**1 = **π** as *k* → ∞ with a speed in the order of *λ*2/*λ*1 exponentially.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This follows because $|\lambda _{2}|\geq \cdots \geq |\lambda _{n}|,$ hence *λ*2/*λ*1 is the dominant term.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The smaller the ratio is, the faster the convergence is.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Random noise in the state distribution **π** can also speed up this convergence to the stationary distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov chain $(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is defined by a finite or countable state space *S*, a transition rate matrix *Q* with dimensions equal to that of the state space and initial probability distribution defined on the state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] For *i* ≠ *j*, the elements *q**ij* are non-negative and describe the rate of the process transitions from state *i* to state *j*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The elements *q**ii* are chosen such that each row of the transition rate matrix sums to zero, while the row-sums of a probability transition matrix in a (discrete) Markov chain are all equal to one.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] There are three equivalent definitions of the process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Let $X_{t}$ be the random variable describing the state of the process at time *t*, and assume the process is in a state *i* at time *t*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Then, knowing $X_{t}=i$ , $X_{t+h}=j$ is independent of previous values $\left(X_{s}:s<t\right)$ , and as *h* → 0 for all *j* and for all *t*, $\Pr(X(t+h)=j\mid X(t)=i)=\delta _{ij}+q_{ij}h+o(h),$ where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, using the little-o notation.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The $q_{ij}$ can be seen as measuring how quickly the transition from *i* to *j* happens.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Define a discrete-time Markov chain *Y**n* to describe the *n*th jump of the process and variables *S*1, *S*2, *S*3, ... to describe holding times in each of the states where *S**i* follows the exponential distribution with rate parameter −*q**Y**i**Y**i*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] with initial condition P(0) is the identity matrix.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] "Locally interacting Markov chains" are Markov chains with an evolution that takes into account the state of other Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This corresponds to the situation when the state space has a (Cartesian-) product form.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] See interacting particle system and stochastic cellular automata (probabilistic cellular automata).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] See for instance *Interaction of Markov Processes* or.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Many results for discrete-time Markov chains with finite state space can be generalized to chains with uncountable state space through Harris chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The use of Markov chains in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods covers cases where the process follows a continuous state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The definition of Markov processes in continuous time with general state space is more technical than the above.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov process $X=(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a stochastic process adapted to a filtration $\mathbb {F} =({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ with values in a locally compact Polish space $(S,{\mathcal {B}}(S))$ (e.g., $(\mathbb {R} ,{\mathcal {B}}(\mathbb {R} ))$ ).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The latter essentially ensures that the conditional expectations of $X_{t}$ are regular, which, in simple terms, means that they behave "nicely".
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The function $(t,x,A)\mapsto P_{t}(x,A)$ is the so-called *transition function* of X and $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ the *transition semigroup* of the process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Transition functions are generalizations of the transition matrices used in the setting with finite state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] where $\delta _{x}$ is the Dirac-measure in x , and $X:\Omega \times [0,\infty )\to S$ .
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Or, if no probability measure P has been specified, the above equation defines a measure $P^{x}:=P(\cdot \mid X_{0}=x)$ on $\sigma (X_{s}:s\geq 0)$ under which the process X started in x is a Markov process by construction.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, Markov processes can be defined either as stochastic processes X on a filtered probability space, or indirectly in terms of a transition semigroup (i.e., the transition probabilities of the process), which induces a probability space under which X has the Markov property.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Two states are said to *communicate* with each other if both are reachable from one another by a sequence of transitions that have positive probability.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This is an equivalence relation which yields a set of communicating classes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A class is *closed* if the probability of leaving the class is zero.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is *irreducible* if there is one communicating class, the state space.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* has period *k* if *k* is the greatest common divisor of the number of transitions by which *i* can be reached, starting from *i*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The state is *periodic* if $k>1$ ; otherwise $k=1$ and the state is *aperiodic*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *transient* if, starting from *i*, there is a non-zero probability that the chain will never return to *i*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] It is called *recurrent* (or *persistent*) otherwise.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] State *i* is *positive recurrent* if $M_{i}$ is finite and *null recurrent* otherwise.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Periodicity, transience, recurrence and positive and null recurrence are class properties — that is, if one state has the property then all states in its communicating class have the property.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is called *absorbing* if there are no outgoing transitions from the state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since periodicity is a class property, if a Markov chain is irreducible, then all its states have the same period.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In particular, if one state is aperiodic, then the whole Markov chain is aperiodic.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If a finite Markov chain is irreducible, then all states are positive recurrent, and it has a unique stationary distribution given by $\pi _{i}=1/E[T_{i}]$ .
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *ergodic* if it is aperiodic and positive recurrent.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In other words, a state *i* is ergodic if it is recurrent, has a period of 1, and has finite mean recurrence time.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If all states in an irreducible Markov chain are ergodic, then the chain is said to be ergodic.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Equivalently, there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] It can be shown that a finite state irreducible Markov chain is ergodic if it has an aperiodic state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain with more than one state and just one out-going transition per state is either not irreducible or not aperiodic, hence cannot be ergodic.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call any irreducible, positive recurrent Markov chains ergodic, even periodic ones.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In fact, merely irreducible Markov chains correspond to ergodic processes, defined according to ergodic theory.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call a matrix *primitive* if there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The *index of primitivity*, or *exponent*, of a regular matrix, is the smallest k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The exponent is purely a graph-theoretic property, since it depends only on whether each entry of M is zero or positive, and therefore can be found on a directed graph with $\mathrm {sign} (M)$ as its adjacency matrix.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] There are several combinatorial results about the exponent when there are finitely many states.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If a Markov chain has a stationary distribution, then it can be converted to a measure-preserving dynamical system: Let the probability space be $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ , where $\Sigma$ is the set of all states for the Markov chain.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Let the sigma-algebra on the probability space be generated by the cylinder sets.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Let the probability measure be generated by the stationary distribution, and the Markov chain transition.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Similarly we can construct such a dynamical system with $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ instead.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Since *irreducible* Markov chains with finite state spaces have a unique stationary distribution, the above construction is unambiguous for irreducible Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In ergodic theory, a measure-preserving dynamical system is called *ergodic* if any measurable subset S such that $T^{-1}(S)=S$ implies $S=\emptyset$ or $\Omega$ (up to a null set).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Given a Markov chain with a stationary distribution that is strictly positive on all states, the Markov chain is *irreducible* if its corresponding measure-preserving dynamical system is *ergodic*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] In some cases, apparently non-Markovian processes may still have Markovian representations, constructed by expanding the concept of the "current" and "future" states.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] For example, let *X* be a non-Markovian process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Then define a process *Y*, such that each state of *Y* represents a time-interval of states of *X*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If *Y* has the Markov property, then it is a Markovian representation of *X*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] An example of a non-Markovian process with a Markovian representation is an autoregressive time series of order greater than one.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The *hitting time* is the time, starting in a given set of states, until the chain arrives in a given state or set of states.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The distribution of such a time period has a phase type distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The simplest such distribution is that of a single exponentially distributed transition.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] For a general Markov process X in continuous time (a CTMC or a process with general state space), the reverse process ${\overleftarrow {X}}=(X_{T-t})_{t\in [0,T]}$ from a fixed time $T>0$ is again a Markov process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] This follows directly from the Markov property: Informally speaking, the future and the past are independent given the present.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Under time-reversal, their roles are just interchanged.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] However, the reverse process is not time-homogeneous in general.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] If X is a CTMC, then by Kelly's lemma ${\overleftarrow {X}}$ has the same stationary distribution as the forward process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A chain is said to be *reversible* if the reversed process is the same as the forward process (in distribution).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov's criterion states that the necessary and sufficient condition for a Markov chain to be reversible is that the product of transition rates around a closed loop must be the same in both directions.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] One method of finding the stationary probability distribution, π, of an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain, *Q*, is by first finding its **embedded Markov chain (EMC)**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Strictly speaking, the EMC is a regular discrete-time Markov chain, sometimes referred to as a **jump process**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Each element of the one-step transition probability matrix of the EMC, *S*, is denoted by *s**ij*, and represents the conditional probability of transitioning from state *i* into state *j*.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] where *I* is the identity matrix and diag(*Q*) is the diagonal matrix formed by selecting the main diagonal from the matrix *Q* and setting all other elements to zero.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] with $\varphi$ being a row vector, such that all elements in $\varphi$ are greater than 0 and $\|\varphi \|_{1}$ = 1.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] (*S* may be periodic, even if *Q* is not.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Another discrete-time process that may be derived from a continuous-time Markov chain is a δ-skeleton—the (discrete-time) Markov chain formed by observing *X*(*t*) at intervals of δ units of time.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The random variables *X*(0), *X*(δ), *X*(2δ), ... give the sequence of states visited by the δ-skeleton.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Markov models are used to model changing systems.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme is a special case of a Markov chain where the transition probability matrix has identical rows, which means that the next state is independent of even the current state (in addition to being independent of the past states).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme with only two possible states is known as a Bernoulli process.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Note, however, by the Ornstein isomorphism theorem, that every aperiodic and irreducible Markov chain is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; thus, one might equally claim that Markov chains are a "special case" of Bernoulli schemes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism generally requires a complicated recoding.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism theorem is even a bit stronger: it states that *any* stationary stochastic process is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; the Markov chain is just one such example.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] When the Markov matrix is replaced by the adjacency matrix of a finite graph, the resulting shift is termed a **topological Markov chain** or a **subshift of finite type**.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] A Markov matrix that is compatible with the adjacency matrix can then provide a measure on the subshift.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p01] Many chaotic dynamical systems are isomorphic to topological Markov chains; examples include diffeomorphisms of closed manifolds, the Prouhet–Thue–Morse system, the Chacon system, sofic systems, context-free systems and block-coding systems.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains have been employed in a wide range of topics across the natural and social sciences, and in technological applications.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] For example, a thermodynamic state operates under a probability distribution that is difficult or expensive to acquire.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Therefore, Markov Chain Monte Carlo method can be used to draw samples randomly from a black-box to approximate the probability distribution of attributes over a range of objects.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in lattice QCD simulations.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The enzyme (E) binds a substrate (S) and produces a product (P).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Each reaction is a state transition in a Markov chain.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] A reaction network is a chemical system involving multiple reactions and chemical species.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The simplest stochastic models of such networks treat the system as a continuous time Markov chain with the state being the number of molecules of each species and with reactions modeled as possible transitions of the chain.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains and continuous-time Markov processes are useful in chemistry when physical systems closely approximate the Markov property.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] For example, imagine a large number *n* of molecules in solution in state A, each of which can undergo a chemical reaction to state B with a certain average rate.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Perhaps the molecule is an enzyme, and the states refer to how it is folded.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The state of any single enzyme follows a Markov chain, and since the molecules are essentially independent of each other, the number of molecules in state A or B at a time is *n* times the probability a given molecule is in that state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The classical model of enzyme activity, Michaelis–Menten kinetics, can be viewed as a Markov chain, where at each time step the reaction proceeds in some direction.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] While Michaelis-Menten is fairly straightforward, far more complicated reaction networks can also be modeled with Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm based on a Markov chain was also used to focus the fragment-based growth of chemicals in silico towards a desired class of compounds such as drugs or natural products.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] As a molecule is grown, a fragment is selected from the nascent molecule as the "current" state.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] It is not aware of its past (that is, it is not aware of what is already bonded to it).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] It then transitions to the next state when a fragment is attached to it.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The transition probabilities are trained on databases of authentic classes of compounds.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Also, the growth (and composition) of copolymers may be modeled using Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Based on the reactivity ratios of the monomers that make up the growing polymer chain, the chain's composition may be calculated (for example, whether monomers tend to add in alternating fashion or in long runs of the same monomer).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Due to steric effects, second-order Markov effects may also play a role in the growth of some polymer chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Similarly, it has been suggested that the crystallization and growth of some epitaxial superlattice oxide materials can be accurately described by Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in various areas of biology.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used throughout information processing.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Such idealized models can capture many of the statistical regularities of systems.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Even without describing the full structure of the system perfectly, such signal models can make possible very effective data compression through entropy encoding techniques such as arithmetic coding.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] They also allow effective state estimation and pattern recognition.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains also play an important role in reinforcement learning.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also the basis for hidden Markov models, which are an important tool in such diverse fields as telephone networks (which use the Viterbi algorithm for error correction), speech recognition and bioinformatics (such as in rearrangements detection).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The LZMA lossless data compression algorithm combines Markov chains with Lempel-Ziv compression to achieve very high compression ratios.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are the basis for the analytical treatment of queues (queueing theory).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Agner Krarup Erlang initiated the subject in 1917.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] This makes them critical for optimizing the performance of telecommunications networks, where messages must often compete for limited resources (such as bandwidth).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Numerous queueing models use continuous-time Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The PageRank of a webpage as used by Google is defined by a Markov chain.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] It is the probability to be at page i in the stationary distribution on the following Markov chain on all (known) webpages.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] If N is the number of known webpages, and a page i has $k_{i}$ outgoing links from it then it has transition probability ${\frac {\alpha }{k_{i}}}+{\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are linked to and ${\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are not linked to.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The parameter $\alpha$ is taken to be about 0.85.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov models have also been used to analyze web navigation behavior of users.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] A user's web link transition on a particular website can be modeled using first- or second-order Markov models and can be used to make predictions regarding future navigation and to personalize the web page for an individual user.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain methods have also become very important for generating sequences of random numbers to accurately reflect very complicated desired probability distributions, via a process called Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] In recent years this has revolutionized the practicability of Bayesian inference methods, allowing a wide range of posterior distributions to be simulated and their parameters found numerically.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in finance and economics to model a variety of different phenomena, including the distribution of income, the size distribution of firms, asset prices and market crashes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Champernowne built a Markov chain model of the distribution of income in 1953.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Simon and co-author Charles Bonini used a Markov chain model to derive a stationary Yule distribution of firm sizes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Louis Bachelier was the first to observe that stock prices followed a random walk.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The random walk was later seen as evidence in favor of the efficient-market hypothesis and random walk models were popular in the literature of the 1960s.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Regime-switching models of business cycles were popularized by James D.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Hamilton (1989), who used a Markov chain to model switches between periods of high and low GDP growth (or, alternatively, economic expansions and recessions).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] A more recent example is the Markov switching multifractal model of Laurent E.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Fisher, which builds upon the convenience of earlier regime-switching models.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] It uses an arbitrarily large Markov chain to drive the level of volatility of asset returns.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Dynamic macroeconomics makes heavy use of Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] An example is using Markov chains to exogenously model prices of equity (stock) in a general equilibrium setting.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Credit rating agencies produce annual tables of the transition probabilities for bonds of different credit ratings.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are generally used in describing path-dependent arguments, where current structural configurations condition future outcomes.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] An example is the reformulation of the idea, originally due to Karl Marx's *Das Kapital*, tying economic development to the rise of capitalism.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are employed in algorithmic music composition, particularly in software such as Csound, Max, and SuperCollider.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] In a first-order chain, the states of the system become note or pitch values, and a probability vector for each note is constructed, completing a transition probability matrix (see below).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm is constructed to produce output note values based on the transition matrix weightings, which could be MIDI note values, frequency (Hz), or any other desirable metric.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] A second-order Markov chain can be introduced by considering the current state *and* also the previous state, as indicated in the second table.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Higher, *n*th-order chains tend to "group" particular notes together, while 'breaking off' into other patterns and sequences occasionally.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] These higher-order chains tend to generate results with a sense of phrasal structure, rather than the 'aimless wandering' produced by a first-order system.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used structurally, as in Xenakis's Analogique A and B.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also used in systems which use a Markov model to react interactively to music input.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Usually musical systems need to enforce specific control constraints on the finite-length sequences they generate, but control constraints are not compatible with Markov models, since they induce long-range dependencies that violate the Markov hypothesis of limited memory.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] In order to overcome this limitation, a new approach has been proposed.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used to model many games of chance.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] The children's games Snakes and Ladders and "Hi Ho!
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Cherry-O", for example, are represented exactly by Markov chains.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] At each turn, the player starts in a given state (on a given square) and from there has fixed odds of moving to certain other states (squares).
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain models have been used in advanced baseball analysis since 1960, although their use is still rare.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Each half-inning of a baseball game fits the Markov chain state when the number of runners and outs are considered.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] During any at-bat, there are 24 possible combinations of number of outs and position of the runners.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Mark Pankin shows that Markov chain models can be used to evaluate runs created for both individual players as well as a team.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] He also discusses various kinds of strategies and play conditions: how Markov chain models have been used to analyze statistics for game situations such as bunting and base stealing and differences when playing on grass vs.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes can also be used to generate superficially real-looking text given a sample document.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes are used in a variety of recreational "parody generator" software (see dissociated press, Jeff Harrison, Mark V.
[src:diffusion-models/markov-chain-p02] Several open-source text generation libraries using Markov chains exist.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In machine learning, a **variational autoencoder** (**VAE**) is an artificial neural network architecture introduced by Diederik P.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] It is part of the families of probabilistic graphical models and variational Bayesian methods.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Thus, the encoder maps each point (such as an image) from a large complex dataset into a distribution within the latent space, rather than to a single point in that space.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The decoder has the opposite function, which is to map from the latent space to the input space, again according to a distribution (although in practice, noise is rarely added during the decoding stage).
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] By mapping a point to a distribution instead of a single point, the network can avoid overfitting the training data.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Both networks are typically trained together with the usage of the reparameterization trick, although the variance of the noise model can be learned separately.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Although this type of model was initially designed for unsupervised learning, its effectiveness has been proven for semi-supervised learning and supervised learning.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] A variational autoencoder is a generative model with a prior and noise distribution respectively.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Usually such models are trained using the expectation-maximization meta-algorithm (e.g. probabilistic PCA, (spike & slab) sparse coding).
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Such a scheme optimizes a lower bound of the data likelihood, which is usually computationally intractable, and in doing so requires the discovery of q-distributions, or variational posteriors.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] These q-distributions are normally parameterized for each individual data point in a separate optimization process.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] However, variational autoencoders use a neural network as an amortized approach to jointly optimize across data points.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In that way, the same parameters are reused for multiple data points, which can result in massive memory savings.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The first neural network takes as input the data points themselves, and outputs parameters for the variational distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] As it maps from a known input space to the low-dimensional latent space, it is called the encoder.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The decoder is the second neural network of this model.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] It is a function that maps from the latent space to the input space, e.g. as the means of the noise distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] It is possible to use another neural network that maps to the variance, however this can be omitted for simplicity.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In such a case, the variance can be optimized with gradient descent.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] To optimize this model, one needs to know two terms: the "reconstruction error", and the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D).
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Both terms are derived from the free energy expression of the probabilistic model, and therefore differ depending on the noise distribution and the assumed prior of the data, here referred to as p-distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] For example, a standard VAE task such as IMAGENET is typically assumed to have a gaussianly distributed noise; however, tasks such as binarized MNIST require a Bernoulli noise.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The KL-D from the free energy expression maximizes the probability mass of the q-distribution that overlaps with the p-distribution, which unfortunately can result in mode-seeking behaviour.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The "reconstruction" term is the remainder of the free energy expression, and requires a sampling approximation to compute its expectation value.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] More recent approaches replace Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D) with various statistical distances, see "Statistical distance VAE variants" below.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] From the point of view of probabilistic modeling, one wants to maximize the likelihood of the data x by their chosen parameterized probability distribution $p_{\theta }(x)=p(x|\theta )$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] This distribution is usually chosen to be a Gaussian $N(x|\mu ,\sigma )$ which is parameterized by $\mu$ and $\sigma$ respectively, and as a member of the exponential family it is easy to work with as a noise distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Simple distributions are easy enough to maximize, however distributions where a prior is assumed over the latents z results in intractable integrals.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Let us find $p_{\theta }(x)$ via marginalizing over z .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] where $p_{\theta }({x,z})$ represents the joint distribution under $p_{\theta }$ of the observable data x and its latent representation or encoding z .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In the vanilla variational autoencoder, z is usually taken to be a finite-dimensional vector of real numbers, and $p_{\theta }({x|z})$ to be a Gaussian distribution.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Then $p_{\theta }(x)$ is a mixture of Gaussian distributions.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Unfortunately, the computation of $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ is expensive and in most cases intractable.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] with $\phi$ defined as the set of real values that parametrize q .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] This is sometimes called *amortized inference*, since by "investing" in finding a good $q_{\phi }$ , one can later infer z from x quickly without doing any integrals.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In this way, the problem is to find a good probabilistic autoencoder, in which the conditional likelihood distribution $p_{\theta }(x|z)$ is computed by the *probabilistic decoder*, and the approximated posterior distribution $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ is computed by the *probabilistic encoder*.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Parametrize the encoder as $E_{\phi }$ , and the decoder as $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Like many deep learning approaches that use gradient-based optimization, VAEs require a differentiable loss function to update the network weights through backpropagation.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] For variational autoencoders, the idea is to jointly optimize the generative model parameters $\theta$ to reduce the reconstruction error between the input and the output, and $\phi$ to make $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ as close as possible to $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] As reconstruction loss, mean squared error and cross entropy are often used.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The Kullback–Leibler divergence $D_{KL}(q_{\phi }({z|x})\parallel p_{\theta }({z|x}))$ can be used as a loss function to squeeze $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ under $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] That is, maximizing the log-likelihood of the observed data, and minimizing the divergence from the approximate posterior $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ to the exact posterior $p_{\theta }(\cdot |x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] That is, we model the distribution of x conditional on z to be a Gaussian distribution centered on $D_{\theta }(z)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] For a more detailed derivation and more interpretations of ELBO and its maximization, see its main page.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] To efficiently search for $\theta ^{*},\phi ^{*}={\underset {\theta ,\phi }{\operatorname {argmax} }}\,L_{\theta ,\phi }(x)$ the typical method is gradient descent.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The **reparameterization trick** (also known as stochastic backpropagation) bypasses this difficulty.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The most important example is when $z\sim q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ is normally distributed, as ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu _{\phi }(x),\Sigma _{\phi }(x))$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] This can be reparametrized by letting ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,{\boldsymbol {I}})$ be a "standard random number generator", and construct z as $z=\mu _{\phi }(x)+L_{\phi }(x)\epsilon$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Since we reparametrized z , we need to find $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Let $q_{0}$ be the probability density function for $\epsilon$ , then $\ln q_{\phi }(z|x)=\ln q_{0}(\epsilon )-\ln |\det(\partial _{\epsilon }z)|$ where $\partial _{\epsilon }z$ is the Jacobian matrix of z with respect to $\epsilon$ .
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Many variational autoencoders applications and extensions have been used to adapt the architecture to other domains and improve its performance.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] $\beta$ -VAE is an implementation with a weighted Kullback–Leibler divergence term to automatically discover and interpret factorised latent representations.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] With this implementation, it is possible to force manifold disentanglement for $\beta$ values greater than one.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] This architecture can discover disentangled latent factors without supervision.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The conditional VAE (CVAE), inserts label information in the latent space to force a deterministic constrained representation of the learned data.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Some structures directly deal with the quality of the generated samples or implement more than one latent space to further improve the representation learning.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Some architectures mix VAE and generative adversarial networks to obtain hybrid models.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] It is not necessary to use gradients to update the encoder.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] In fact, the encoder is not necessary for the generative model.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] Kingma and Max Welling, several procedures were proposed to formulate in a more abstract way the operation of the VAE.
[src:diffusion-models/variational-autoencoder] The statistical distance d requires special properties, for instance it has to be possess a formula as expectation because the loss function will need to be optimized by stochastic optimization algorithms.
